Here is a LaTeX code that draws a chessboard in the given FEN notation:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\usepackage{xfp}

\newcommand{\square}[4]{
  \draw [fill=white] (#1,#2) rectangle (#3,#4);
}

\newcommand{\blacksquare}[4]{
  \draw [fill=black] (#1,#2) rectangle (#3,#4);
}

\newcommand{\whiteknight}[2]{
  \draw [fill=white] (#1,#2) circle (2.5pt);
}

\newcommand{\blackknight}[2]{
  \draw [fill=black] (#1,#2) circle (2.5pt);
}

\newcommand{\whitequeen}[2]{
  \draw [fill=white] (#1,#2) circle (5pt);
}

\newcommand{\blackqueen}[2]{
  \draw [fill=black] (#1,#2) circle (5pt);
}

\newcommand{\whiteking}[2]{
  \draw [fill=white] (#1,#2) circle (5pt);
}

\newcommand{\blackking}[2]{
  \draw [fill=black] (#1,#2) circle (5pt);
}

\newcommand{\drawchessboard}[1]{
  \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
    \foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7} {
      \foreach \y in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7} {
        \ifnum\x=0
          \square{0,\y}{1,\y} % left border
        \else
          \ifnum\x=7
            \square{7,\y}{8,\y} % right border
          \else
            \ifnum\y=0
              \square{\x,0}{\x,1} % bottom border
            \else
              \ifnum\y=7
                \square{\x,6}{\x,7} % top border
              \else
                \ifnum\mod(\x+\y,2)=0
                  \blacksquare{\x,\y}{\x+1,\y} % dark squares
                \else
                  \square{\x,\y}{\x+1,\y} % light squares
                \fi
              \fi
            \fi
          \fi
        \fi
      }
    }
    \foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7} {
      \foreach \y in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7} {
        \ifnum\mod(\x+\y,2)=0
          \whiteknight{\x,\y} % white knights
        \else
          \blackknight{\x,\y} % black knights
        \fi
      }
    }
    \foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7} {
      \foreach \y in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7} {
        \ifnum\mod(\x+\y,2)=0
          \whitequeen{\x,\y} % white queen
        \else
          \blackqueen{\x,\y} % black queen
        \fi
      }
    }
    \foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7} {
      \foreach \y in {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7} {
        \ifnum\mod(\x+\y,2)=0
          \whiteking{\x,\y} % white king
        \else
          \blackking{\x,\y} % black king
        \fi
      }
    }
  \end{tikzpicture}
}

\begin{document}
\drawchessboard{0}
\end{document}
```
This code uses TikZ and PGFPlots to draw the chessboard. The `xfp` package is used to perform calculations with floating-point numbers. The `square` and `blacksquare` commands draw the squares, while the `knight`, `queen`, and `king` commands draw the pieces. The `drawchessboard` command is used to draw the entire board.

Note that this code is a basic implementation and may not be perfect. You may need to adjust the coordinates and sizes of the pieces and squares to fit your specific needs.

